<subsubsection xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title> Terms </title>

	<p>
		A differential equation is constructed from <em>terms</em>, each separated by either a plus (<m>+</m>), minus (<m>-</m>), or equal (<m>=</m>) sign. For example, the differential equation 
		<men xml:id="de-terms-equation">
			\frac{3}{x}	y^{(6)} + 5.3 y'' + x^2 (y')^3 - y = \frac12\ln(x)
		</men>
		has five terms. Each term is associated to the dependent variable it contains. If a term does not contain a dependent variable, it is called a <term>constant term</term>. We can list out the terms in the equation above as follows:
	</p>

	<p>
		<tabular halign="center">
			<col width="20%" />
			<col width="20%" />
			<col width="20%" />
			<col width="20%" />
			<col width="20%" />
			
			<row>
				<cell><p><m>\ul{y^{(6)}\text{ term}}</m></p></cell><cell/>
				<cell><p><m>\ul{y''\text{ term}}</m></p></cell><cell/>
				<cell><p><m>\ul{(y')^3\text{ term}}</m></p></cell><cell/>
				<cell><p><m>\ul{y\text{ term}}</m></p></cell><cell/>
				<cell><p><m>\ul{\text{constant term}}</m></p></cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell><p><m>\ds \frac{3}{x} y^{(6)}</m></p></cell><cell/>
				<cell><p><m>\ds\vphantom{\frac11} 5.3 y''</m></p></cell><cell/>
				<cell><p><m>\ds\vphantom{\frac11} x^2 (y')^3</m></p></cell><cell/>
				<cell><p><m>\ds\vphantom{\frac11} -y</m></p></cell><cell/>
				<cell><p><m>\ds \frac12\ln(x)</m></p></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>
	</p>

	<p>
		Note that every differential equation has at least a zero constant term. For example, the equation <m>y' = -3y</m> can be written as <m>y' + 3y = 0</m>, showing a <m>0</m> constant term on the right-side.
	</p>

	<p>
		As we progress, you'll see how the types and arrangements of terms in a differential equation guide us in choosing the right solution techniques.
	</p>
	
	<xi:include href="./chkpts-1-2-2-terms.ptx" />

</subsubsection>